15
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Maybe for folks, we should give a little bit of background on what a lab leak implies. Is there a precedent for such a thing in virology?

16
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:41,000
Because at the surface, it certainly sounds nefarious, right? It sounds like, well, that must be a deliberate thing. And it immediately falls into the realm of conspiracy theories.

17
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:55,000
But in fact, there's quite a precedent for viruses getting out of labs in the modern era. And I would define the modern era as the era of microbiology. Obviously, there weren't lab leaks that accounted for the Spanish flu.

18
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:04,000
But are there any that come to mind as you began your work here or that you had to learn about as a result of your investigation?

19
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:13,000
Yeah. So let me say first that lab leak, as it's understood, is not a unitary theory.

20
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:37,000
It ranges all the way from field researchers went into a bat cave, brought back natural samples into a laboratory, and that natural sample somehow leaked or a laboratory researcher got infected simply through aerosol transmission, which is what we're talking about.

21
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:46,000
This is not, I mean, the word leak implies like liquid gushing out of a pipe. That's not what we're talking about. We're talking about aerosol transmission.

22
00:03:46,000 --> 00:04:06,000
But it could have been an infected lab worker. It could have been an infected field researcher bringing a sample back. But the phrase lab leak sort of runs all the way up to the possibility that someone in a laboratory was manipulating viruses potentially

23
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:23,000
in an experiment to make them more infectious, to see if they would become more infectious, and that that new strain, not a natural strain, per se, but one that was genetically modified, could have leaked from a laboratory.

24
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:42,000
So it really runs the gamut. It's not a single thing. And yes, you know, lab leak. This is not like, oh, how could that ever happen? In a way, it's like, how could it not happen? Because it's happened over and over and over again.

25
00:04:42,000 --> 00:05:04,000
You know, you had very serious lab leak in the Soviet Union, which finally became exposed. It was an anthrax leak. You've had SARS leaks. You've had four SARS lab escapes since the SARS epidemic of 2002. So this actually is something that happens a lot.

26
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:33,000
And it seems that one of the most significant examples of this was this Russian flu in 1977, which was an H1N1 flu that had been around in the 40s and 50s. It was being studied in a lab. When it reemerged, it seemed to target disproportionately people that were younger than 25, which at the time maybe didn't make sense, although after it was clear that this was the same virus that was around.

27
00:05:33,000 --> 00:06:03,000
So it made sense because obviously the people that were being afflicted were people that did not develop natural immunity. Again, there had been no, to my knowledge, of course, because you wouldn't have had the tools to have done so, there was no gain of function. Not that they could have genetically edited, but I don't believe there was evidence that it had been sort of selectively bred or anything like that. It was simply a question of this is a virus that's being studied in a lab. And then somehow that led to it getting out. And as you point out, at least four cases of the virus that was being

28
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:11,000
early SARS-1 virus escaping. And again, when you read the stories of these, which I've read at one point, all of them,

29
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:25,000
it's these are mistakes that people can make. These are perhaps viruses that are not being handled with as much care as they should be handled. Some shortcuts are being taken with respect to how they could be handled.

30
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:48,000
You know, I think it's important to point out that people talk about, you know, BSL-4 labs that are studying these incredibly dangerous pathogens. And so those are the most protective, highest containment labs where all the researchers are working in spacesuits with independent oxygen.

31
00:06:48,000 --> 00:07:09,000
But the fact of the matter on the ground is that you have research with incredibly dangerous pathogens taking place in laboratories across the world that have much less protection, like BSL-2 labs, which are basically the safety standard of an American dentist's office.

32
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:28,000
You know, so you've had live SARS viruses being studied in overcrowded laboratories, you know, in China and elsewhere with very little protection, very few protections.

33
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:42,000
So there's at least a precedent that a virus that's being studied can make its way out of the lab. In fact, there's a great precedent for it. But of course, that alone doesn't explain what could have happened here.

34
00:07:42,000 --> 00:08:04,000
