52
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:45,000
So there's a couple of really interesting things about about what happened in 2012. First of all, that it happened, what happened, but also how it came, how it sort of broke into the public domain. What happened?

53
00:12:46,000 --> 00:13:06,000
So just starting out in 2012, there were six miners who were given this very unpleasant assignment, which was to go to this abandoned mine shaft and dig, clean it out because it was thick with bat guano, which is bat feces, essentially.

54
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:27,000
So they go in there and they dig for days and weeks and they become gravely ill. So they become admitted to the hospital and in Kunming University Hospital, so they get admitted to the hospital.

55
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:45,000
The question is, is it a fungus? Is it a virus? They bring in an expert who analyzed this says it's a virus. They have pneumonia. It's a virus. Their symptoms were almost identical to COVID-19.

56
00:13:46,000 --> 00:14:00,000
So he asked, what were they doing? They were digging up bat guano. What kind of bat? It's this Chinese rufous horseshoe bat, which is the same one that triggered SARS-CoV-1.

57
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:15,000
Three of the miners died. Three ultimately recovered. So this is a case that should have triggered worldwide alarm because it looked like the beginning of an outbreak again.

58
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:36,000
But the Chinese authorities never reported this to the World Health Organization. It sort of remained below the radar, except that this abandoned mine shaft became a destination for virologists in Asia who were going into this mine shaft and getting samples and bringing it back to their laboratories.

59
00:14:37,000 --> 00:15:00,000
Probably the most active samplers from this mine shaft were members of the Wuhan Institute of Virology in Wuhan. They dug up many samples, brought it back to their laboratories, and they sequenced a sample, which they called at the time 4991.

60
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:20,000
And that was, as we would find out later, 96.2% identical to SARS-CoV-2. Except at the beginning of the outbreak, nobody knew about this mine shaft. Nobody knew that three miners had died, and no one knew about 4991.

61
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:45,000
The only way that we ultimately found out about it is because a very curious, unemployed science teacher in eastern India started digging into this database of Chinese master's thesis and pulled up an entire dissertation about this incident in the mine shaft.

62
00:15:45,000 --> 00:16:04,000
Now, to be clear, it would not have been known based on the infection of those six mine shaft workers with basically a 50% mortality that there was any evidence that that virus could be transmitted human to human. Correct?

63
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:19,000
It could have been simply that they acquired it from the bats, which is the most likely scenario in the presence of an overwhelming exposure to the virus, but that the virus would not transmit human to human. Would that have been possible?

64
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:31,000
That's right. That's right. We have no information that they infected one another. They were all exposed to this bat guano. They went to the hospital.

65
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:49,000
It doesn't appear that the hospital workers got sick, so it doesn't appear that they spread it to other people, but they were desperately ill. And it's interesting to note, the oldest miner died first. He was the most gravely afflicted. He was in his 60s.

66
00:16:49,000 --> 00:17:07,000
So if we look back at this incident in light of COVID-19, there are a number of aspects of this that do look like SARS-CoV-2 in 2012.

67
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:25,000
Though clearly it's a different virus given that, I mean, I think for a person listening, maybe not familiar with genetic distance, 96.2% sounds like, oh, that's a perfect match. But of course, that's not remotely a match.

68
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:43,000
