00:50:47,000 --> 00:50:58,000
The BBC sent a team of journalists there in December of 2020. They were tailed by Chinese police. They found a big truck blocking access to the mine shaft.

192
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:10,000
The Wall Street Journal sent a reporter in on a bicycle and he was detained by Chinese police and questioned for about five hours.

193
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:19,000
And, you know, his notes were confiscated. So the Chinese government has been blocking access to this mine shaft.

194
00:51:19,000 --> 00:51:31,000
So let's talk about some of the lines of evidence both for and against this. I mean, I think what's what's clear here is one, there's a precedent for this happening. Right.

195
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:51,000
So it's an absolutely plausible scenario. Two, unfortunately, because of the nature of the Chinese government's behavior and by extension, the US government's behavior, there's ample reason to believe in a conspiracy.

196
00:51:51,000 --> 00:52:02,000
But by no means is that necessary. In other words, this virus could have completely occurred in nature and the Chinese government would probably still behave the exact way it did.

197
00:52:02,000 --> 00:52:15,000
And the US government would have behaved exactly the same way it did. So, you know, unfortunately, those things don't really, I think, move the thinking or the evidence one way or the other more than the other.

198
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:31,000
But now let's talk about some of the features of the virus, because I think this is where it gets very I mean, not that not that not that what we've said hasn't gotten interesting, but but the biology of this is also quite interesting. Right.

199
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:55,000
Yeah. So, you know, there has been a lot of let me first say that I don't think there there is no information that is in the public domain, either regarding the viral sequence and the sort of oddities of the viral sequence, you know, or regarding other

200
00:52:55,000 --> 00:53:13,000
circumstantial evidence that can answer this question one way or another. You know, you when I started reporting this, there was, you know, there were plenty of articles that were like, well, maybe this and maybe that, you know, but the information that is in the public domain doesn't get you there.

201
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:41,000
Some attention or a lot of attention has been focused on what is called a furin cleavage site in the sequence. And that is, you know, part of the strain that one virologist told me is a sort of signature of genetic editing of the Wuhan Institute of Virology, that in a number of the strains they've worked on and manipulated and

202
00:53:41,000 --> 00:53:43,000
published papers about, you see the insertion of a furin cleavage site in the in the viral sequence. And that is the spot on the sequence that makes it more infectious to humans. So Nick Wade, who's a former New York Times reporter, you know, he published a long piece sort of analyzing the question of the science and the

203
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:51,000
science and the science of the human body. And I think that's a very interesting question.

204
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:35,000
That was he told his wife, that was the smoking gun, you know, and then he knew it was genetically edited. Since Nick Wade's piece came out and got a lot of attention, David Baltimore sort of walked that back and said, well, not really.

205
00:54:35,000 --> 00:54:46,000
And then other people have come out and said, well, you find furin cleavage sites and sequences in nature, and it doesn't necessarily have to be reflective of genetic editing.

206
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:54,000
That's been my find as well. I mean, I've spent far more time on this than I wanted to, because it's one of those.

207
00:54:54,000 --> 00:54:55,000
Everybody does.

208
00:54:55,000 --> 00:55:04,000
Yeah, it's one of those things you sort of think, well, look, I'm going to just read these three articles and then but then you have to read every single reference to those articles.

209
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:13,000
