210
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:22,000
But, you know, that's one of the rabbit holes I went incredibly far down. And there's just outright contradictory information there.

211
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:34,000
Now, I haven't spoken to Nicholas Wade, but in his piece, he says there is no evidence of furin cleavage sites in any beta coronaviruses that are SARS like.

212
00:55:34,000 --> 00:55:49,000
And yet I actually found several references for papers that contradict that, including a paper published in 2018 that found a furin cleavage site in MERS, which is a SARS like beta coronavirus.

213
00:55:49,000 --> 00:56:00,000
So to me, the presence of the furin cleavage site, which to your point makes this much more infectious than SARS one.

214
00:56:00,000 --> 00:56:09,000
You had commented that that SARS one, you know, it transmits through the ACE, the ACE two receptor.

215
00:56:09,000 --> 00:56:20,000
Well, this is on the order of like an order of magnitude more transmissible because that S1, S2 subunit is cleaved and now it has an enormous affinity for that ACE two receptor.

216
00:56:20,000 --> 00:56:32,000
So a more interesting question to me is the nature of the codons that exist there. So the furin cleavage site is always a or not.

217
00:56:32,000 --> 00:56:47,000
Actually, I believe it is. I believe it is exclusively a proline, arginine, arginine, alanine sequence. And not to bore people with too much biochemistry, but you have three nucleotides that make up each codon.

218
00:56:47,000 --> 00:56:57,000
So you have redundancy in the system because there's only 20 amino acids, but you have 64 combinations with all of the nucleotides.

219
00:56:58,000 --> 00:57:13,000
You have more than one way to get an amino acid. So what I think also got a lot of attention in Nick Wade's piece was the I think it's a CGG arginine.

220
00:57:13,000 --> 00:57:29,000
And that is a very unusual arginine. It's only typically present in 5% of coronaviruses, meaning only 5% of the time when a coronavirus needs to make an arginine, does it use a I think it's CCG or CGG.

221
00:57:30,000 --> 00:57:44,000
Okay. But when you go and look more deeply in the literature, it turns out that you saw that in other furin cleavage sites of other coronaviruses that also had very little of that.

222
00:57:44,000 --> 00:57:55,000
In other words, there was another coronavirus that I saw that only had 3% of its arginines being either CCG or CGG, but it still showed up in its furin cleavage site.

223
00:57:55,000 --> 00:58:05,000
And there's no ambiguity about whether that was naturally occurring or not. So does that mean it occurred in nature? Does that mean it was manipulated in a lab? It's still very hard to know.

224
00:58:05,000 --> 00:58:22,000
So I don't think really in any dimension of this, there is no smoking gun per se. What there is is smoke coming out of a lot of windows.

225
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:38,000
You know, that's what I saw as I was reporting. There is enough smoke coming out of enough windows that we cannot take the lab leak hypothesis off the table.

226
00:58:38,000 --> 00:58:50,000
And so for me, the most credible people on this, they're not saying it was a lab leak. What they're saying is, why can't we have a full investigation?

227
00:58:50,000 --> 00:59:06,000
That's what we don't have. We have not had a forensic investigation. And so if we haven't had a forensic investigation, why are the scientists acting so unscientific by saying it wasn't a lab leak?

228
00:59:06,000 --> 00:59:16,000
How do they know? They don't actually know. Just like we don't know that it was or it wasn't.

229
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:26,000
But there is enough of a suspicious fact pattern that it requires investigation.

230
00:59:26,000 --> 00:59:38,000
Yeah. Of all the things that I have read, and I think at this point, I don't know what I haven't read. I feel like it's just so overwhelming. I think the most compelling.

231
00:59:38,000 --> 00:59:41,000
Welcome to the club. Yes.

232
00:59:41,000 --> 01:00:01,000
I think the most compelling mechanistic answer. So there's lots of circumstantial reasons, right? The Lockham's razor says, you know, in the middle of fall slash winter. So in Q4 of 2019, when there are no bats, they're all hibernating.

233
01:00:01,000 --> 01:00:25,000
You have a breakout in a major population center that's doing research on it. So all of those things aside, from a purely biological mechanistic standpoint, I think the most convincing piece of evidence for a lab leak is that for about a year post this virus being in humans, it didn't change.

234
01:00:25,000 --> 01:00:51,000
We're only now seeing variants of this virus, right? Like the Delta variant you mentioned earlier. That strikes me as interesting given that given the ubiquity of this virus, so how many people were infected, suggesting just how stable this thing was by the time it got into humans, meaning a lot of the tinkering got taken out of it sooner.

235
01:00:51,000 --> 01:01:07,000
Now, so one argument would be if this were a virus that got manipulated and naturally selected through humanized mice, which is to say mice that have ACE2 receptors in their lungs, which are the exact mice you would use to do this type of research.

236
01:01:07,000 --> 01:01:25,000
In fact, the mice, which we know were being used for this type of research. Yes. That makes sense to me that, you know, you could easily have a virus that has now reached its state of maturation. It gets out now into, you know, the wild.

237
01:01:25,000 --> 01:01:40,000
And it takes quite a while to evolve into its new variant. What about you? Like, where does that stack up in terms of biological reasoning in favor of a lab leak versus not?

238
01:01:41,000 --> 01:02:09,000
So, you know, there are one scientist, Alina Chan. She's at the Broad Institute. And she has really advanced that idea and had a preprint paper to that effect, which is the idea that this virus seemed immediately ready to infect humans and didn't appear to undergo the sort of all the early mutations

239
01:02:09,000 --> 01:02:30,000
that you saw in SARS-CoV-1, right? So it seemed sort of primed for human transmission, which in her view argued for a lab leak. But then you have scientists on the other side of that who say, actually, if you look at this strain, this is not maximized for human infectivity.

240
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:44,000
If you were going to set out to create this in a laboratory to maximize human infectivity, this isn't it. So I think those are, again, two competing versions of this.

241
01:02:44,000 --> 01:02:56,000
But they're saying very different things. Like, I don't think that Alisa, is it Alisa Chen is her name? Alina. Alina Chen. I don't think her argument is that it's maximized in its potential.

242
01:02:56,000 --> 01:03:15,000
I think if I'm understanding her argument correctly, it's that it's reached a steady state. It's in an equilibrium. And I think that's a very different argument to the one that's being posed in the other direction, which is that, oh, well, if you were going to make this, you could make a much better job.

243
01:03:15,000 --> 01:03:26,000
I think that maybe gives a little too much credit to scientists. Like, you know, it's sort of like saying, well, you know, when those bombs dropped on Hiroshima, I mean, they were good, but they weren't as good as they could have been.

244
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:42,000
I mean, come on, they could have been way more lethal. No, no, I mean, like, you know, I have to say that it is sort of a red herring argument because, OK, so let's say it's not like the perfect bio weapon to infect all of humanity overnight.

245
01:03:42,000 --> 01:03:56,000
That wasn't its intended purpose. Right. The credible people who talk about a lab leak are not necessarily saying it was a bio weapon. It could be the accident of a sloppy, you know, a moment of momentary laughs.

246
01:03:56,000 --> 01:04:21,000
Yeah. So again, I've always found that argument to be completely nonsensical because one, if we believe in the broad idea of gain of function research, it's not bio weaponry to even if you say, well, no, but if you're going to go to the trouble of doing gain of function research, you should try to make the most virulent, deadly strain imaginable.

247
01:04:21,000 --> 01:04:35,000
OK, but are you going to make that in the first, you know, let's assume it takes 100 steps to make that. And what happened if we were at step 60 when this leak occurred? Right. Does that mean we weren't on a path to making it better?

248
01:04:35,000 --> 01:04:42,000
So so again, to me, that argument is meaningless, actually. Right. There is a there's a lot there are a lot of red herrings in this debate.

249
01:04:43,000 --> 01:05:11,000
So given all this sort of loose smoke that's sort of diffusing from the ground out of windows here and there, how would you think about trying to synthesize the arguments that most favor the consensus view that this virus occurred naturally versus the contrarian view, for lack of a better word, that this virus emerged from a lab?

250
01:05:11,000 --> 01:05:21,000
What would you say are the most compelling features that favor the former? First, let me just say that I actually don't think there is a consensus view at this time.

251
01:05:21,000 --> 01:05:40,000
I think the consensus has been shattered and the scientific community is really divided. That said, I think, you know, the strongest argument for a zoonotic origin is the precedent of precedent.

252
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:59,000
A precedent of previous of previous SARS outbreaks, you know, SARS-CoV-1 and MERS. And you look at those and yeah, those are SARS outbreaks that have a zoonotic origin that has been identified.

253
01:05:59,000 --> 01:06:09,000
Right. So it would make perfect sense that this would this is the big one. You know, this has come on the heels of those outbreaks.

254
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:29,000
You know, and you add into that, you don't have any specific smoking gun evidence to contradict that. Right. Even though a host animal has not been found, an intermediate animal has not been found.

255
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:37,000
So I think those, you know, that in and of itself is sort of the most basic, the most basic argument for it.

256
01:06:38,000 --> 01:07:05,000
And to build on that really, you know, SARS-1 traveled something like 900 to 1000 miles from its original site using two intermediary hosts. So to your point, the argument that, well, if this originated in a bat in a cave 1000 miles away, there's no way it could make it to this populated area. No, that's not true. It certainly happened in the past, right?

257
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:25,000
It certainly has happened in the past. But let me just say that is one of the that is added to the mystery here, because, you know, what people are saying is, well, if it started in southern China in Yunnan Province, why don't we see a trail of infections up to Wuhan? We don't.

258
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:51,000
So it looks like Wuhan in central China is the origin of this outbreak. Why? Right. So the original theory was there is a host animal and it could have been a sample at the seafood market in Wuhan. But no, you know, all of this testing has not turned that up.

259
01:07:52,000 --> 01:08:17,000
So, you know, in order to account for a natural origin, you have to find a way to argue how in the dead of winter in central China, you know, in a market that didn't sell bats, didn't have bats at a time when most bats are hibernating, you know, how do you have how do you have this outbreak?

260
01:08:18,000 --> 01:08:37,000
You know, and then you look at, you know, the Chinese scientists themselves were like, oh, we know where it came from. It came from these labs. Two Chinese scientists very early on in the outbreak posted a preprint paper saying, well, we surveyed the area around the seafood market.

261
01:08:37,000 --> 01:08:54,000
And there are these two laboratories that have all these bat samples. So we think it came from them. And that preprint paper was immediately taken down. But, you know, you have this problem of how to account for how it started in Wuhan.

262
01:08:55,000 --> 01:09:07,000
Now, again, to go back to evidence in favor of the zoonotic origin, it could be because I don't think anybody disputes that the bats weren't transmitting it to people in the fall or winter.

263
01:09:07,000 --> 01:09:22,000
I think everybody agrees that by the time September, October, November rolled around, the bats themselves would have been in hibernation. So the probability that a bat directly transmitted it to a human in, say, November, December, exceedingly low.

264
01:09:23,000 --> 01:09:39,000
Of course, the bats could have passed it on to intermediaries before then and or the bats could have transmitted it on to a person or persons before then who didn't really become that ill but somehow managed to make their way to Wuhan. Correct?

265
01:09:40,000 --> 01:09:54,000
Yes, although there is a wild card in this, which is that the virus in many cases is asymptomatic. So there are people who are arguing for an even earlier origin than we knew.

266
01:09:54,000 --> 01:09:56,000
Such as the summer of 2019.

267
01:09:56,000 --> 01:10:09,000
Right. They're like Dr. Redfield is one of those people who has said that he thinks the origin is actually a lot earlier and that it's very hard to pinpoint a date because of the problem of asymptomatic transmission.

268
01:10:10,000 --> 01:10:36,000
Right. And, you know, you got to take a step back and remember what it was like circa May of 2020 when the very first papers were coming out looking at zero positivity, suggesting that the case fatality rate was, you know, infinitely lower than it had been previously identified.

269
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:46,000
So, you know, when we were first thinking about this as, oh, my gosh, like two percent of people or eight percent of people who are getting this are dying.

270
01:10:46,000 --> 01:10:56,000
And it's the realization was no, it's eight percent of people who are wildly symptomatic are dying or. Right. And then the more we begin to test people, the more that number began to fall.

271
01:10:56,000 --> 01:11:05,000
But it wasn't until serology was being done on asymptomatic people. This was done in Santa Clara, a very controversial study by John Ioannidis.

272
01:11:05,000 --> 01:11:13,000
It was done in New York. You basically began to see, look, this has got a lethality of about one in a thousand people infected.

273
01:11:13,000 --> 01:11:29,000
So if you then extract, you know, that back to China, there's a scenario in which 500 people are infected, none of whom really get sick or think anything of it beyond, you know, it's just a it's a regular cold.

274
01:11:29,000 --> 01:11:40,000
But, you know, someone threads that needle of getting up to Wuhan. So that there's at least a plausibility of bat to human to Wuhan in that timeframe. Correct.

275
01:11:40,000 --> 01:11:51,000
Correct. That is right. Yes. If that were the case, it's would still be interesting to identify the bat of origin, but it sounds like that's not happening yet.

276
01:11:51,000 --> 01:11:58,000
So let's chalk that up to first on our our wish list. Right. So we were creating a wish list of how one would get to the bottom of this.

277
01:11:58,000 --> 01:12:10,000
It would be a full court press to identify, you know, to do basically an amazing prospecting exercise to look for the bat host potentially.

278
01:12:10,000 --> 01:12:20,000
But but but just to say that in a way has been done. Right. That's potentially what's in the database that was taken out in 2009 in September of 2019.

279
01:12:20,000 --> 01:12:35,000
But even since, you know, since the covid outbreak and and so that is post dating what was in the database, there has been a huge hunt and widespread testing of wildlife samples.

280
01:12:35,000 --> 01:12:41,000
I mean, there has been a big, big hunt for the host animal, which has not been found.

281
01:12:41,000 --> 01:12:47,000
And has that hunt been carried out mostly by Chinese scientists or has been a worldwide effort?

282
01:12:47,000 --> 01:13:08,000
It's been a worldwide effort, but, you know, the Chinese authorities have tested. I mean, the the count and and the WHO report talks about this, something like 80,000 animal samples have been tested in search of a point of origin and has not been found.

283
01:13:08,000 --> 01:13:23,000
OK, so then on the heels of that, another scenario is that a bat infected an intermediary, which either infected humans or another intermediary, which ultimately infected humans.

284
01:13:23,000 --> 01:13:30,000
Several of those animals have been proposed and several of those animals could have existed at the Wuhan market in the winter.

285
01:13:30,000 --> 01:13:34,000
It's been found that the animal was, you know, a very large animal.

286
01:13:34,000 --> 01:13:40,000
And yet it's still alive, still alive, not necessarily kept in the most sanitary conditions.

287
01:13:40,000 --> 01:13:44,000
That seems like a very viable scenario.

288
01:13:44,000 --> 01:13:54,000
And the biggest challenge to that is that very few stones have been left unturned in the search for what those animals might be.

289
01:13:54,000 --> 01:14:03,000
So, you know, that is a very logical scenario, except that there's no evidence for it. That's the problem.

290
01:14:03,000 --> 01:14:05,000
Other than precedent.

291
01:14:05,000 --> 01:14:08,000
Correct. Yeah.

292
01:14:08,000 --> 01:14:21,000
So I just want to make sure I'm not missing a scenario. Is there any other scenario that involves this virus infecting people having not been to a lab first?

293
01:14:22,000 --> 01:14:42,000
You know, one thing that has been talked about is the people who live around these bat caves, who have had exposure, who have tested positive and larger numbers previously for SARS antibodies.

294
01:14:43,000 --> 01:15:00,000
You know, but you still have the same problem of if that is the or if that is a possible origin is a natural escape in location in southern China to villagers who live around those mines.

295
01:15:00,000 --> 01:15:10,000
How does it get up to Wuhan without leaving a trail of infection that could be documented? Right. That's the that's the problem.

296
01:15:11,000 --> 01:15:37,000
Right. So then on the other side, we have a scenario where researchers are identifying this virus by identifying its original host and themselves get infected through that, bring the bats or the virus itself into the lab.

297
01:15:37,000 --> 01:15:51,000
And early in their tenure with these animals or with the virus rather, there's a contamination. I mean, I really think of these as two sides of the same coin, which is gain a function versus no gain a function research.

298
01:15:51,000 --> 01:15:59,000
But nevertheless, the virus has been brought into the lab. I mean, that's basically the other side of this coin. That's right.

299
01:15:59,000 --> 01:16:28,000
The most compelling argument for that appears to be at least to my reading, the contrapositive of what we just said, i.e., it's the absence of either the original bat or the intermediary host, coupled with the argument made earlier about the relative lack of genetic drift or mutation once the virus took hold.

300
01:16:29,000 --> 01:16:35,000
In 2019, in late 2019, the stability of the virus, basically.

301
01:16:35,000 --> 01:16:54,000
You know, I think here, first of all, there is there is a lot of precedent for a lab leak, as we've seen. I mean, there is a long there is a long history of this. There is a proximity argument, which is why Wuhan?

302
01:16:54,000 --> 01:17:12,000
Well, here are these laboratories that have the largest collection of bat samples really in the world who were doing some of the most aggressive testing. So, you know, there's that smoke coming out of that window.

303
01:17:12,000 --> 01:17:28,000
We know that they were doing aggressive gain of function research in which they were manipulating pathogens. And we also know that they were doing it not just in a BSL-4 setting, but in a BSL-2 setting.

304
01:17:28,000 --> 01:17:50,000
And then you do have the Alina Chan argument that, you know, you do not see the sort of wide range of mutations initially in transmission that you did with SARS-CoV-1. So I think there's those arguments.

305
01:17:50,000 --> 01:18:05,000
Yeah, and I guess you could almost break this down into two arguments, which is what's the likelihood that this virus was brought into or created in a lab versus what's the likelihood it escaped?

306
01:18:05,000 --> 01:18:21,000
The second probab- so you could break this down into two probabilities, probability that this virus was brought into a lab and then really a third one, probability that this was manipulated in a lab and then probability that this thing escaped or could have escaped.

307
01:18:21,000 --> 01:18:48,000
So if that's P1, P2, P3, P3 is like close to one. That could be taken as a foregone conclusion, meaning the probability that a virus in a lab can get out is very high. We know about the bad ones that have happened, but what we don't know is how many times has, you know, research been done on a virus in a lab that is of totally no consequence to humans and it gets out.

308
01:18:48,000 --> 01:19:02,000
We wouldn't know about it, but that could happen all the time. So if you're supposed to be functioning at BSL-4- and by the way, I mean, I'm not saying this to sort of pick on the people doing it. BSL-4 is a miserable environment.

309
01:19:02,000 --> 01:19:29,000
Like you couldn't pay me enough to be a viral researcher working in a BSL-4 environment. I would rather be painting roofs with tar in July than I would be working in a BSL-4 lab. So I can totally understand why there's a natural human inclination to take shortcuts with procedure there.

310
01:19:29,000 --> 01:19:40,000
So I almost think of like that third step of could this have escaped the lab as of course it could have. So it's really just a question of what's the likelihood that this thing made its way into a lab and got tweaked.

311
01:19:40,000 --> 01:19:58,000
And that's where you get into these other questions of, boy, the people who claim it didn't aren't doing themselves any favors in the way they're acting. You know, the EcoHealth Alliance, the Lancet paper doesn't look good in the way that they're acting.

312
01:19:58,000 --> 01:20:02,000
It doesn't look good in the light of day.

313
01:20:02,000 --> 01:20:26,000
No, it does not look good. You know, which is back to one of the groups that I talk about in my Vanity Fair article is this group that calls themselves drastic, which are these scientists who are independent researchers scattered around the globe who became, you know, curious about this, obsessed by this,

314
01:20:26,000 --> 01:20:35,000
wanted to get to the bottom of it. But, you know, I interviewed a number of them. How many of them are anonymous versus identified, by the way?

315
01:20:35,000 --> 01:20:51,000
There's a handful who are anonymous. And I did not write about any of those who were anonymous who I didn't speak with because you really cannot assess the agenda of someone who is anonymous and you're not interviewing.

316
01:20:51,000 --> 01:21:12,000
I mean, you don't know whether it's, you know, Steve Bannon hiding behind a pseudonym. So but, you know, for example, the Indian researcher who calls himself the seeker on Twitter, he's a science teacher in eastern India who was the one who uncovered this Chinese master's thesis.

317
01:21:12,000 --> 01:21:22,000
I was able to interview him. You know, a lot of those people I interviewed, they said the same thing to me.

318
01:21:22,000 --> 01:21:30,000
I got into this because I wanted to know why the scientists were asking, acting so unscientific.

319
01:21:30,000 --> 01:21:46,000
You know, why do you take a hypothesis off the table without evidence? Right. If you're having an investigation, don't you pursue all hypotheses in an equal fashion until you have real evidence.

320
01:21:46,000 --> 01:22:13,000
And in fact, you know, the World Health Organization partnered with a group of experts who went to China and were basically sort of led on this, you know, highly restricted tour by the Chinese authorities and issued a report in which they said, oh, the lab leak hypothesis is highly unlikely.

321
01:22:13,000 --> 01:22:30,000
I obtained a U.S. government analysis of that report, which said, you know, the report is essentially ridiculous. It concludes that on the basis of no evidence. And in fact, one of the lead researchers on that expedition was Peter Daschak of EcoHealth Alliance.

322
01:22:30,000 --> 01:22:40,000
So, you know, there has not been a neutral. Wasn't Peter Daschak the only American brought in? Wasn't he the only American scientist brought in? Yes, he was.

323
01:22:40,000 --> 01:22:52,000
So there has not been a neutral conflict free forensic evaluation of all possibilities of origin at this time.

324
01:22:52,000 --> 01:23:06,000
Do you have confidence that such a thing will happen? The Biden administration recently requested such a report to be delivered within no less than 90 days, if I'm not mistaken.

325
01:23:06,000 --> 01:23:30,000
Yeah. It is going to take a huge act of political will and really unity by many, many different countries to essentially force the Chinese to be more transparent.

326
01:23:30,000 --> 01:23:47,000
It's not necessarily a fight that the Biden administration wants to have. It's really inconvenient. I think it would be a whole lot easier to say, well, it must be zoonotic and we can't find the animal host bummer.

327
01:23:47,000 --> 01:24:04,000
So, you know, I don't know if we're going to be able to surmount all of the political hurdles and the evidentiary hurdles that lay in our way to have a real investigation into this.

328
01:24:04,000 --> 01:24:14,000
And what would be required of full transparency? What would be asked for that would demonstrate conclusively one way or the other?

329
01:24:14,000 --> 01:24:34,000
Well, you know, part of that is what probably will never happen. China says, you know what? We're changing our minds, full transparency. We're putting back the database. Here's a record of all the samples. Here are the lab notebooks.

330
01:24:34,000 --> 01:24:45,000
Come to a tour. Here's the medical records of all the researchers who were in the laboratory. That is very, very unlikely to happen.

331
01:24:45,000 --> 01:24:56,000
We, by the way, have no serology on the three people who worked in the lab who got sick in the late summer, early fall of 2019, correct?

332
01:24:56,000 --> 01:25:05,000
My understanding is that we don't or if we do, if our intelligence agencies are more definitive, it's definitely not in the public domain.

333
01:25:05,000 --> 01:25:17,000
So, you know, plan B, assuming that China is not going to be more forthcoming, is for the countries of the world to basically look in their own research files.

334
01:25:18,000 --> 01:25:31,000
You know, that there is a lot of information that is potentially available to us if we are really to dig into our own filing cabinets. That is essentially what Joe Biden has called for.

335
01:25:31,000 --> 01:25:44,000
He's told the intelligence agencies to go back to the drawing board, inventory what they have, and see if they can't come to some sort of closer conclusion.

336
01:25:45,000 --> 01:26:10,000
You know, there was recently an important paper put forth by Jesse Bloom, who is an esteemed virologist, who said that there were sequences that were in an NIH database that were taken offline at the request of Chinese scientists that had some early sequences from Wuhan.

337
01:26:10,000 --> 01:26:22,000
So potentially, you know, there is information that our own government, for whatever reason, has either buried or ignored or removed, which can be analyzed.

338
01:26:22,000 --> 01:26:38,000
So given all the time you've spent on this so far, how has your own probability shifted from zoonotic versus lab origin over the past year?

339
01:26:39,000 --> 01:26:56,000
Right. Well, you know, starting out when anybody mentioned the possibility of a lab leak, I was very dismissive because it sounded to me just like conspiracy theories. And there were a lot of conspiracy theories associated with that.

340
01:26:57,000 --> 01:27:17,000
But I think what's happened is, as time has gone on, and no host animal has been found, and Trump has been removed, and so there is a sort of space to ask this question without necessarily aiding what's viewed as a racist agenda.

341
01:27:18,000 --> 01:27:26,000
You know, and China has failed to be transparent, and conflicts of interest have been exposed.

342
01:27:28,000 --> 01:27:40,000
You know, and from my own reporting now, I understand that a full investigation within the US government was essentially blocked or restricted.

343
01:27:41,000 --> 01:27:58,000
You know, I kind of give it even odds at this point. I think it's a possibility. I don't have a definite conclusion. You know, if a host animal was found tomorrow, I would be like, okay.

344
01:27:59,000 --> 01:28:05,000
But I think there are just too many questions to be ignored right now.

345
01:28:06,000 --> 01:28:19,000
You know, one of the things about conspiracy theories is they require coverups. You know, they, you know, one of the one of the conspiracy theories that's always obsessed me is the Kennedy assassination ever since I was a kid.

346
01:28:20,000 --> 01:28:31,000
And I don't know, probably by the time I was in my mid 30s, I'd seen enough read enough that I concluded there's simply no way it was anything other than Lee Harvey Oswald.

347
01:28:32,000 --> 01:28:39,000
Like I really just decided, despite what Oliver Stone would have you believe, Lee Harvey Oswald acted alone.

348
01:28:40,000 --> 01:28:52,000
And there are many reasons I could bore you with that include a more accurate looking at, you know, more accurate look at the forensics of the, you know, the, the, the ballistics and things like that.

349
01:28:53,000 --> 01:29:06,000
But a big part of it is how hard would it be to keep everybody quiet if this were some CIA plot or some mob plot or, you know, one of the other crazy ideas that's put forth.

350
01:29:07,000 --> 01:29:20,000
And I guess that's one of the things that kind of nags at me here a little bit with this one, which is if this in fact came from a lab, how many people have to know that? Right?

351
01:29:21,000 --> 01:29:33,000
It's not the case, by the way, that that Peter Daschig would necessarily know that right? He wouldn't necessarily know that. I mean, he might have a huge incentive to hope that it's not happened, but he wouldn't necessarily know that.

352
01:29:34,000 --> 01:29:48,000
But, but presumably more than one person would be covering this up. Right? And I guess that speaks to the bigger that number of people, the harder this thing becomes over time. If indeed that's the case.

353
01:29:49,000 --> 01:30:02,000
So let me say a couple of things about this. You know, first of all, the question of COVID origin is the ultimate grassy knoll. Right? You know, this is one for the ages.

354
01:30:02,000 --> 01:30:31,000
I think the question of a cover up, you know, it's very different to consider a cover up in the U.S. with a tradition of freedom of speech and protection of whistleblowers and to consider a cover up in China with an authoritarian government that has control over everybody's lives and can act absolutely wreak havoc, not just on a whistleblower, but on a whistleblower's family.

355
01:30:32,000 --> 01:30:52,000
So, for example, the anthrax lab leak in the Soviet Union in the 70s only became disclosed after the fall of the Soviet Union. Right? Once this sort of authoritarian structure around it crumbled, then it could be disclosed.

356
01:30:52,000 --> 01:31:09,000
But, you know, China has incredible control over its citizens and could even if, let's say, She Zhengli thinks it was a lab leak or knows it was a lab leak, is she free to say that?

357
01:31:09,000 --> 01:31:21,000
Well, certainly not well in China and not well her family's. Right. Yeah. So, you know, that said, I'm always mindful of this expression we have in investigative journalism.

358
01:31:22,000 --> 01:31:40,000
Never assume conspiracy when incompetence is an option. In other words, you know, it's easy to say conspiracy, but that's always a more unlikely possibility.

359
01:31:41,000 --> 01:31:58,000
Yeah, conspiracy doesn't make a lot of sense here. And I think it detracts from an honest look at the facts. It should really be viewed as two competing hypotheses and one of them that got largely ignored because because it was politically inconvenient to consider.

360
01:31:58,000 --> 01:32:06,000
Yes, that's that's right. That's I side with that analysis. 100 percent.

361
01:32:07,000 --> 01:32:22,000
Are you optimistic that a year from now we're going to have much more insight? Because the reality of it is if you're if you look at what we know today versus what we knew six months ago, virtually nothing new. Right.

362
01:32:22,000 --> 01:32:35,000
Very little new information. There's just been more attention paid to old information, which is always concerning when you're trying to think about this. Right. Because, you know, it's more interesting if, oh, my goodness, there's a lot of information.

363
01:32:35,000 --> 01:32:47,000
There's a lot of information that is emerging here. We are learning more, but that's not really the case. We're learning more on the basis of old information. And at some point, we're going to saturate our knowledge based on that.

364
01:32:47,000 --> 01:32:57,000
Are you optimistic that we're going to learn more in the next year or is this going to become simply more of a polarizing discussion?

365
01:32:57,000 --> 01:33:14,000
Well, I have no doubt that it will be a polarizing discussion and continue to be one. I think the real question, the way I see it, is how much political capital does the Biden administration want to spend on this?

366
01:33:14,000 --> 01:33:26,000
The Biden administration and the other powerful governments of the world. How far are they willing to push China to demand answers?

367
01:33:26,000 --> 01:33:42,000
Well, of course, someone in China knows some answer, presumably like they know it was or wasn't a lab leak or they can guess that. How far are the governments of the world prepared to go to push for an answer for this?

368
01:33:42,000 --> 01:33:51,000
You know, besides the United States, who? Yeah. Who? Besides the United States, which governments would have the most persuasion?

369
01:33:51,000 --> 01:34:15,000
You know, a lot of this is going to be fought economically. So, for example, originally, the government of Australia, of Scott Morrison, was pushing to have the question of a lab leak as part of the sort of one of the facets of the World Health Organization inquiry into this.

370
01:34:15,000 --> 01:34:39,000
They wanted to make sure that that possibility got on the agenda. China's retaliation was very swift and they were immediately blocked. I believe it was import of Australian goods into China. So there is a lot of economic retaliation that can occur in the push for answers.

371
01:34:39,000 --> 01:34:56,000
And as we've already kind of identified, there's no scenario under which a lab leak occurred and the United States doesn't have blood on its hands as well through both direct contribution of funding and also collaboration from a research perspective, correct?

372
01:34:56,000 --> 01:35:15,000
I mean, in other words, if there's a lab leak, you know, you can't just say, well, it's just the fault of the Wuhan Institute of Virology because it's just bad luck that it occurred there. The reality is this could have easily taken place at the University of North Carolina or the University of Galveston in Texas where similar research goes on.

373
01:35:15,000 --> 01:35:24,000
The bigger issue is this was in some ways a joint effort between the United States and China, correct?

374
01:35:24,000 --> 01:35:41,000
Well, let me just say there is one other laboratory that is right near the Huanan seafood market, which is the Chinese Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, which had moved right next to the seafood market shortly before the outbreak began.

375
01:35:41,000 --> 01:35:57,000
They had a coronavirus researcher who was very gung-ho had collected a lot of viral samples. So I guess in theory, it is possible that this came from a laboratory that had nothing to do with U.S. funding.

376
01:35:57,000 --> 01:36:16,000
But I would say, you know, regardless, I still take your point that the lab leak scenario raises a lot of thorny questions for the National Institutes of Health, for how scientific research is funded.

377
01:36:16,000 --> 01:36:27,000
You know, it would be hell to pay in the field of virology if the effort to identify viruses ended up unleashing them.

378
01:36:27,000 --> 01:36:40,000
Yeah, it's interesting to think how this will unfold over the coming decade, the economic damage, the loss of life, etc.

379
01:36:40,000 --> 01:36:49,000
Do you get a sense of how this will impact gain-of-function research, at least in the United States?

